        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Modelling the detached shell of U Ant

The detached shell was modelled using the 3-d radiative transfer code LIME (Brinch &amp; Hogerheijde 2010). We assumed a shell mass of 2x10-3 Msun (Schöier et al. 2005) and 10,000 identical clumps randomly distributed throughout a shell with radius 43". Each clump has a FWHM of 1.9". We estimate a peak line flux of 0.4 Jy/beam at a resolution of 1.25" in the CO(1-0) transition, consistent with single-dish observations (Olofsson et al. 1996). The resulting images are simulated using simobserve in CASA for the respective ALMA configuration (see below). Figure 3 in the scientific justification shows the CASA simulation of the proposed CO(1-0) observations.

Proposed ALMA observations of U Ant

Spatial scales: The thin (approx 2-3") and clumpy (typical scales of less than approx. 2") detached shell around U Ant has a radius of approx. 43". The entire shell can be covered in a 27-pointing mosaic in band 3, at a resolution of 1.25", covering an 115" x 115" field, allowing us to resolve the clumpy structure in the shell. Including the ACA we expect to fully recover the total flux. The single-dish measurements by Olofsson et al. (1996) are available to us for comparison. Moreover, complementary APEX observations are foreseen. 

Spectral setup: Observations of low-lying transitions of CO are an extensively used method to probe the molecular gas in the circumstellar envelopes of AGB stars. We will observe the entire shell in CO in band 3 using frequency division mode and dual polarisation. We aim for a velocity resolution of 1.27 km/s (Hanning smoothed), sufficient for a total line width of 40 km/s and local turbulent wind velocities of typically 1-2 km/s. This setup allows us to place 2 basebands chosen to cover the CO(1-0)line in band 3 at 115.27 (117.2 MHz width and spectral averaging of 16). We additionally cover the CN(1-0) line at 113.12 GHz (937.5 MHz width and spectral averaging of 1 - in order to cover the entire hyperfine structure). 

The remaining spectral windows are positioned and sized to give broad (2 GHz) continuous regions to cover continuum emission. Line free regions will provide additional continuum information of the central source. The expected continuum emission is 0.5 mJy in band 3.

Time estimate: A total observing time (incl. main array and ACA time, calibrations and all pointings) of 3.5 hours in band 3 gives a sensitivity of 0.02 Jy/beam, allowing us to detect the weakest (i.e. 20% of peak flux) parts of the detached shell in CO(1-0) with a S/N=4, and the strongest emission at a S/N=20. Figure 3 depicts the expected CO(1-0) observation from a CASA simulation as detailed in the technical setup. </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
