    <prp:abstract>We propose to observe the circumstellar environment around the carbon AGB star U Ant in the CO(1-0) and CO(2-1) transitions. Mass loss on the AGB still remains a puzzle, and in particular temporal variations in the mass-loss rate during and after a thermal pulse are uncertain. The observed data will spatially resolve (on 1.25” scales) the detached shell at 43" around U Ant, the structure intrinsic to the shell, the multiple shells inside the detached shell, and the morphology of the mass loss. The spectral resolution (1.25 km/s) will allow us to determine the dynamical structure of the gas. Using 3-dimensional radiative transfer models, we will constrain the mass and temperature of the gas. Combined with hydrodynamical models we will be able to determine the mass-loss history of the star since the creation of the detached shell, and the connection to thermal pulses.  The proposed observations will give is the most detailed view of U Ant to date, both spectrally and spatially. Ultimately the proposed observations will increase our knowledge of the mass-loss on the AGB in connection with thermal pulses – the most dominant part of the late evolution of solar-type stars. </prp:abstract>
